CHAPTER XVII.  VERY SHY THINGS.   Mrs. Lovejoy sat far away from all the worry, and flurry, and fun of picking, and packing, and covering up.
She had never entirely given herself to the glories of fruit-growing; and she never could be much convinced that any glory was in it.
She belonged to a higher rank of life than any of such sons of Cain.
Her father had been a navy-captain; and her cousin was Attorney-General.
This office has always been confounded, in the provincial mind, with rank in a less pugnacious profession.
Even Mrs. Lovejoy thought, when the land was so full of âmilitiamen,â that her cousin was the General of the âDevilâs Ownâ of the period.
