Then he dwelled bitterly over his fate, for having to go and fetch his pony, and let every yokel look into his basket and grin at its beautiful emptiness.
Moreover, he found himself face to face with starvation of the saddest kind; that which a man has challenged, and superciliously talked about, and then has to meet very quietly.
Not to exaggerate--if that were possible--Mr. Hales found his inner man (thus rashly exposed to new Kentish air) âabsolutely barking at him,â as he strongly expressed it to his wife, as soon as he was truly at home again.
But here he was fifty miles from home, with not a fishing-basket only, but a much nearer and dearer receptacle, full of the purest vacuity.
âThis is very sad,â he said; and all his system echoed it.
