â
âWe will speak no more upon this matter,â Claudia answered, magnanimously.
And the nurse thenceforth was ready to vow, and Hilary only too glad to believe, that the sorely wounded soldier owed his life to a beautiful maiden.
And so he did; but not to Claudia.
CHAPTER XLII.  AN UNWELCOME ESCORT.   Along the northern brow and bend of the Sussex hills, the winter lingers, and the spring wakes slowly.
The children of the southern slope, towards Worthing and West Tarring, have made their cowslip balls, and pranked their hats and hair with blue-bells, before their little northern cousins have begun to nurse and talk to, and then pull to pieces, their cuckoo-pint, and potentilla, dead-nettle, and meadow crowfoot.
The daffodil that comes and âtakes the winds of March with beauty,â here reserves that charming capture for the early breeze of May; for still the âblack-thorn winterâ buffets the folds of chilly Aprilâs cloak, and the hail-fringed mantle of wan sunlight.
This is the time when a man may say, âHurrah!
Here is summer come at last, I verily do believe.
For goodnessâ sake, wife, give us air, and take those hot things from the childrenâs necks.
If you want me, I shall be in the bower, having a jolly pipe at last.
â And then by the time all the windows are open, and the little ones are proud to show their necks and the scratches of their pins, in rushes papa, with his coat buttoned over, and his pipe put out by hail.
None the less for all that, the people who like to see things moving--though it be but slowly--have opportunity now of watching small delights that do them good.
How trees, and shrubs, and plants, and even earth and stone, begin to feel the difference coming over them.
How little points, all black one day, and as hard as the tip of a rookâs bill the next time of looking at them, show a little veiny shining.
And then as the people come home from church, and are in their most observant humour, after long confinement, a little child finds a real leaf (most likely of an elder-tree), and many young faces crowd around it; while the old men, having seen too many springs, plod on and doubt this for a bad one.
Much of this had been done, with slow advance from Sunday to Sunday, and the hedges began to be feathered with green, and the meadows to tuft where the good stuff lay, and the corn in the gloss of the sun to glisten; when everybody came out of church one Sunday before Pentecost.
The church was that which belonged to the Rev.
Struan Hales (in his own opinion), and so did the congregation, and so did everything, except the sermon.
And now the Rector remained in the vestry, with his favourite daughter Cecil, to help him off with his âacademicals,â and to put away his comb.
âI hope your mother will be quick, my dear,â said the Parson, stooping his broad shoulders, as his daughter tugged at him; âshe cannot walk as she used, you know; and for the last half-hour I have been shuddering and trembling about our first fore-quarter.
â
âI saw that you were uncomfortable, papa, just as you were giving out your text.
You seemed to smell something burning, didnât you?
â
âExactly!
â said the Rector, gazing with surprise at his clever and queer Cecil.
âNow how could you tell?
I am sure I hope none of the congregation were up to it.
But 9_d.
_ a pound is no joke for the father of three hungry daughters.
â
âAnd with a good appetite of his own, papa.
Well, Iâll tell you how I knew it.
You have a peculiar way of lifting your nose when the meat is too near the fire, as it always is with our new cook; and then you looked out of that round-arched window, as if you expected to see some smoke.
â
âLift my nose, indeed!
â answered the Rector; âI shall lift something else; I shall lift your lips, if you laugh at your poor old father so.
And I never shaved this morning, because of Sir Remnantâs dinner-party to-morrow.
There, what do you think of that, Miss Impudence?
â
âOh papa, what a shameful beard!
You preached about the stubble being all burned up; perhaps because you were thinking of our lamb.
