â
âWell, of course--of course I do; until you come to know me.
After that, I always listen; because the ladies have more to say.
And they say it so much better.
â
âIs that so?
â said Alice, thinking, while the Captain showed his waist, as he arose and shook himself, âit may be so: he may be right; he seems to have some very good ideas.
â He saw that she thought more kindly of him; and that his proper course with her was to play humility.
He had never known what pure love was; he had lessened his small capacity for it, by his loose and wicked life; but in spite of all that, for the first time Alice began to inspire him with it.
This is a grand revolution in the mind, or the heart, of a âman of pleasure;â the result may save him even yet (if a purer nature master him) from that deadliest foe, himself.
And the best (or the worst of it) is, that if a kind, and fresh, and warm, and lofty-minded girl believes herself to have gained any power of doing good in the body of some low reprobate, sweet interest, Christian hankerings, and the feminine love of paradoxes, succeed the legitimate disgust.
Alice, however, was not of a weak, impulsive, and slavish nature.
And she wholly disdained this Stephen Chapman.
âNow, I hope that you will not hurry yourself,â she said to the pensive captain; âthe real hill begins as soon as we are round the corner.
